Vide Politianam. Mscell. lib. 32. But shortly after, as the Romans of better sort had three names according to that of Juvenal, Tanquam habeas tria nomina, and that of Ausonius, Tria nomina nobiliorum: So it seemed a disgrace for a Gentleman to have but one single name, as the meaner sort, and bastards had. For the daughter and heir of Fitz Hamon a great Lord, (as Robert of Glocester in the Librarie of the industrious Antiquary Master John Stow writeth,) when King Henry the first would have married her to his base son Robert, she first refusing answered;
It were to me a great shame,
To have a Lord withouten his twa name.

And accordingly names were borrowed, as Plutarch saith, from the nature of the man, from his actions, from some marke, forme or deformitie of his body, as Macrinus,
                  Plutarch. in Mario & Sylla. that is, Long: Torquatus, that is, Chained: Gulla, that is, White and Red: And in like sort Mucmon, that is, Mindefull;


                  Grypus, that is, Hawks-nose; Callinicus, that is, Fair Victor.

